The basic list constructor, the double colon, is an infix function. That makes it unusable for vertical code. However, the standard library defines a synonym of :: called yield : func yield : a -> List a -> List a = (::) It's a literal synonym. But, it's a prefix function. How does that help? Take this list: [1, 2, 3] Rewrite it with the colons: 1 :: 2 :: 3 :: empty Cool. Now, how would this look if we used yield instead? yield 1 (yield 2 (yield 3 empty)) All we did was replace all :: s with yield s. And here it comes. Can you see it? We can use the semicolon and make it vertical! yield 1;
yield 2;
yield 3;
empty Beautiful! To get to know yield a little better, let's use it to rewrite some well known functions. How would the map function look like using yield ? Something like this: func my-map : (a -> b) -> List a -> List b = \f \list for list ( \x \next yield (f x); next ); empty The for function isn't just for IO . It can be used with anything that composes vertically. We take the function f and the list and we yield all of its elements in order, except we transform them with f . We can even make the code shorter with function composition: func my-map : (a -> b) -> List a -> List b = \f \list for list (yield . f); empty That's really nice.
